data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere gives unhelpful failure messages like "expected True, got False."

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count assertion with meaningful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users are active - shows which element failed
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check for a specific item
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — shows both values on failure instead of just "False"
- **`CollectionAssert`** — purpose-built for collections:
  - `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)`
  - `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`
  - `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
  - `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — order-sensitive
  - `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — order-insensitive
- **Always add a message string** to `Assert.IsTrue` when you must use it — otherwise failures are undiagnosable.

**Bonus:** If you can add [FluentAssertions](https://fluentassertions.com/) (NuGet), the syntax gets even cleaner:

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```
